docs.abstract: A selection of books published this week; plus, a peek at what our colleagues around the newsroom are reading.
docs.snippet: A selection of books published this week; plus, a peek at what our colleagues around the newsroom are reading.
docs.lead_paragraph: ALL THE FLOWERS KNEELING, by Paul Tran. (Penguin Books, paper, $18.) “My purpose is precision,” Tran writes in this powerful debut, which marshals narrative lyrics and stark beauty (bioluminescence, “ochre-stained shells”) to address personal and political violence. “Even when I’m unclear I’m deliberate. / When I’m deliberate I’m liberated.”

headline.main: Newly Published, From a Vermont Sanctuary to Chicago’s Spoken Word

docs.abstract: Enes Kanter Freedom has condemned human rights abuses in Turkey for years. Now he claims the N.B.A. is blackballing him as he focuses on abuses in China.
docs.snippet: Enes Kanter Freedom has condemned human rights abuses in Turkey for years. Now he claims the N.B.A. is blackballing him as he focuses on abuses in China.
docs.lead_paragraph: “My activism actually started when I was 9 years old,” Enes Kanter Freedom told a rapt audience of pro-democracy activists that included Garry Kasparov, the former world chess champion known for his opposition to President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia.

headline.main: Basketball Skills Got Him to the N.B.A., but Activism Made His Name
headline.print_headline: Now Engaged in a Full-Court Press for Activism

docs.abstract: It won’t be easy, but our democracy depends on it.
docs.snippet: It won’t be easy, but our democracy depends on it.
docs.lead_paragraph: The same information revolution that brought us Netflix, podcasts and the knowledge of the world in our smartphone-gripping hands has also undermined American democracy. There can be no doubt that virally spread political disinformation and delusional invective about stolen, rigged elections are threatening the foundation of our Republic. It’s going to take both legal and political change to bolster that foundation, and it might not be enough.

headline.main: How to Keep the Rising Tide of Fake News From Drowning Our Democracy

docs.abstract: The former “Grey’s Anatomy” star is making his Broadway debut in “Take Me Out.” For that, he said, “I needed to go into a very unknown place.”
docs.snippet: The former “Grey’s Anatomy” star is making his Broadway debut in “Take Me Out.” For that, he said, “I needed to go into a very unknown place.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Jesse Williams will be the first tell you — certainly, he was the first to tell me — that he has no formal theater training and little practice. There’s an Edward Albee play in the hazy past and a one-act opposite Zosia Mamet. That’s pretty much it.

headline.main: So Long, Medical Scrubs. Jesse Williams Is Ready to Play Ball.

docs.abstract: Charles Blow, Roxane Gay and Esau McCaulley join Lulu Garcia-Navarro to discuss why the incident has elicited so many passionate responses.
docs.snippet: Charles Blow, Roxane Gay and Esau McCaulley join Lulu Garcia-Navarro to discuss why the incident has elicited so many passionate responses.
docs.lead_paragraph: Will Smith’s slap has already launched a thousand takes. On Sunday evening at the Academy Awards, the actor struck Chris Rock after the comedian joked about his wife’s shaved head. (Jada Pinkett Smith has alopecia, a condition that leads to hair loss.) Later in the evening, when Smith won his first Oscar, he apologized onstage, saying, “Love will make you do crazy things.”

headline.main: Four Opinion Writers on Will Smith’s Slap: ‘There Are No Heroes in This Story’

byline.original: By Lulu Garcia-Navarro, Charles M. Blow, Roxane Gay and Esau McCaulley

docs.abstract: Claudia Rankine’s heady new play dares white audiences to deny the realities of their social advantages.
docs.snippet: Claudia Rankine’s heady new play dares white audiences to deny the realities of their social advantages.
docs.lead_paragraph: In July 2019, The New York Times Magazine published an essay by the poet and author Claudia Rankine titled, “I Wanted to Know What White Men Thought About Their Privilege. So I Asked.” A first-person investigation of white dominance and its broad range of social consequences, Rankine’s essay prompted more than 2,000 online comments, including many defensive replies from white readers.

headline.main: ‘Help’ Review: Blindfolds (and Kid Gloves) Off. Let’s Analyze Whiteness.
headline.print_headline: Blindfolds (and Kid Gloves) Off: Let’s Talk About Privilege

docs.abstract: The demonstrators camped outside Washington are rallying against Covid restrictions, but are fueled by a far broader set of right-wing grievances.

docs.lead_paragraph: HAGERSTOWN, Md. — As dusk settled over the racetrack on the edge of town, a truck driver stood on a trailer being used as a makeshift stage and held forth on the sins of the politicians in the nation’s capital, an hour and a half’s drive southeast.

headline.main: Trucker Protest Moved by More Than Opposition to Covid Mandates
headline.print_headline: Trucker Protest Settles In For Long Haul to Oppose Mandates, and Far More

docs.abstract: A diverse and kaleidoscopic art exhibition, curated by 17 members of its security staff, spotlights the perspectives of employees typically seen but rarely heard.
docs.snippet: A diverse and kaleidoscopic art exhibition, curated by 17 members of its security staff, spotlights the perspectives of employees typically seen but rarely heard.
docs.lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — Museum guards have been a focal point of unionizing efforts and equity and safety conversations sweeping U.S. museums in the wake of Covid, Black Lives Matter protests and the recent stabbing at MoMA. Yet they have largely remained an anonymous group.

headline.main: Baltimore Museum Guards Take Seats at the Curators’ Table
headline.print_headline: They Guard It. Now They Get to Choose It.

docs.abstract: As leader of a group in Westchester County, N.Y., she was arrested more than 20 times for local and national protests, including ones against nuclear power plants.
docs.snippet: As leader of a group in Westchester County, N.Y., she was arrested more than 20 times for local and national protests, including ones against nuclear power plants.
docs.lead_paragraph: Connie Hogarth, a relentless activist who for nearly a quarter-century led a social justice organization in suburban New York that orchestrated protests against nuclear power and worked on behalf of causes like women’s rights and the environment, died on Feb. 11 at her home in Beacon, N.Y., in Dutchess County. She was 95.

headline.main: Connie Hogarth, Relentless Social Activist, Dies at 95
headline.print_headline: Connie Hogarth, 95, Tireless Activist Who Led a Social Justice Organization
